<span class="displaytext"><i>at rural summit, (candidate last) hears from iowans and rural policy experts</i> <p>tama - (candidate full)'s presidential campaign convened a rural issues summit titled "real change for rural america" in tama today where (candidate last) and rural policy experts talked about making changes to rural policies - including the farm bill - that will strengthen rural america and support family farmers. </p><p>"<i>it's time to turn the page on a politics that has turned its back on rural america,</i>" said (candidate last). "<i>while you're working hard to strengthen your farms, your families, and your communities, our government is working for big agribusiness. in the last decade, we've handed out $1.3 billion in federal farm money to people who aren't even farmers. we've even got farm money going to fortune 500 companies.</i>" </p><p>at one of the summit's policy break-out sessions, (candidate last) heard from iowans who said too many farm bill subsidies went to wealthy corporate farms and not enough to family farmers. (candidate last) agreed that changes need to be made to the farm bill and expressed his support for lowering payment limits and reducing the number of multimillionaires who are eligible for farm bill subsidies.</p><p>"<i>it's time for us to make some changes to the farm bill so we spend fewer resources subsidizing corporate megafarms and more time and resources supporting family farmers and rural america,</i>" said (candidate last). "<i>specifically, we should lower the payment limit to $250,000 annually and make sure those payments go to farmers who need them -- not to millionaire farmers who are relying on the american taxpayers to protect their multi-million dollar profits.</i>" </p><p>speaking at tama high school, (candidate last) cited his experience fighting for the interests of rural illinois communities in the state legislature and the us senate and vowed to continue that fight as president.</p><p>"<i>i've seen the challenges in downstate illinois,</i>" (candidate last) said. "<i>i've fought these battles for rural americans - and for ethics reform in our government - in springfield and in washington. and i know that what we're talking about here is not just one policy - it's about the future for these kids who are going to graduate from tama high. it's about whether they can find opportunity here at home. it's about whether they'll have a government that fights for them, so they can dream without limit.</i>"</p></span>



